The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look into Gaudi's interiors.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric sarian, the staircase with a spinal column of dinosaur and the balconies with open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received the nickname of Maison en os from the premises.
Organic shapes, wild colours, unusual use of stones, piece of tiles and mosaic, façade recalling scales and everywhere present curves, here is all that is epic for Art New by Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house runs its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
A more detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm and order thought accurately.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyeleton and the blades.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district on the street market Passeig de Gracia at the number. 43, was born of the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of old construction and the construction of another new one but quickly accepted the idea of Gaudí's unusual reconstruction and better market.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a house with multiple dwellings was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that decorations were born for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade have also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises nicknamed the house hot just after its finish because of its organic shapes "the House in Bone".
Others, in view of the specific opening mechanism of the windows, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint Georges the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of sculpture of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi has thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with air events and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
In the course of the Gaudi creation, the construction directives were absolutely not complied with and were not allowed to be blocked by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained the building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and demanded changes.
He did not like, for example, the members of the municipal council that construction pillars are impeding on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call from the city Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third one room and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented at a jewelery.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which you can access to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also works on the modern concept of space linkage.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the hall doors and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has also received new facades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the interior courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-coloured game gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark that instead absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued their visits because they found that it was a lucrative business and they expanded the field of visits to common spaces and to the barn including roof terraces.
The entry ticket in the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other buildings of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a friend among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
