Monitoring devices are increasingly required by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think of monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases, such as the example of the small Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The small Anicka case has stirred up a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that it is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of poor use of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons, add Pilin.
According to him, children should always know what "box" is used for and how to use it in the event of an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child doesn't want to wear something like this, he'll get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control.'
"Portable phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared rapture, the author will do everything to ensure that the child has no electronic device to locate it."
"Now it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," said the psychologist.
It also confesses that such devices can help in an attack that is not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it has been destroyed in the case of aggression.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular emission after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The most expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in an extended position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, mobile phones called intelligent ones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after they have formed it with a special software.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the ones that are worn in the pendant of the size of a box of lighters or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can still lose them.
According to Pilina from Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in auto-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
