A longer index than the ring is a low risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than the ring is exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the hormone male testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men before 60 years old," proclaimed the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at Warwick University.
In this way, the finger could help determine which men should submit to the prostate cancer test, including by combining genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
Over the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index shorter than the ring.
For them and for the 19 percent of those with the same length fingers, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the longer index than the annular the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before 60 years the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The length report of the two fingers cited - trained during the prenatal period - indicates, inter alia, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that testosterone helps to develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
