Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it follows the changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the pretty sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries over the South American Pacific (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also increased in Mexico, where the economy improved after having experienced a strong decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, thus reducing the regional average (see table 2).
Some 44% of the respondents in the region said they were satisfied with how their country's democracy worked in practice, with the same figure as last year but with a strong increase of 25% in 2001 (Graph 3)
Some 34 per cent said they had confidence in the Parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a significant increase from 2003 (respectively 17 per cent and 24 per cent).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shook support for democracy.
If this has been good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have suffered only a brief recession and received considerable recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
