The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People need to go to Visa Applicants' Service Centres prior to their interview with the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
With effect from 10 January 2011, the visa processing procedure at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to attend the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASCs) prior to their interview with the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will present some benefits for the applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, no longer need to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The bidder will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visas will not be required to interview the Consular Representative, they will only appear at the nearest AUC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants wishing for a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there for less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolets/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
