Hackers vendors and spies in due course
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears only as a scandal in the face of hypocrisy which governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (from any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinisterly caricature profile had long been for sketch cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files must be composed only new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the earlier books.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (he does not know where to seek news about the non-existent), but because those who want occultism believe only in what they already know, and who confirms what they have already learned.
It's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Same for secret files.
The informer is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the chief of secret services (unless he could be, I know, editor at Libération), who retains only what he recognizes as true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department were the same as the newsweek published earlier this week.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the Heads of State can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into centres of espionage.
Any viewer of an investigation film knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put U.S. diplomacy under a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the state department.
So the scandal does not put the victims and the "burreaux" in such a crisis.
But let us come to the deep nature of what has happened.
At Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been fully proven since, having been able to control each movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as now happens, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - may know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said it, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to remove all power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but he did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this very powerful injury?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on line any information reserved - this would be to publish it on a post glued to the street.
But it's just as obvious that with current technologies, it's worth hoping to be able to maintain confidential phone reports.
Nothing easier than discovering whether and when a head of state moved by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know that for the moment, my prediction comes from science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who discreetly move in due diligence to uncontrollable routes, being only carriers of messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in key closed drawers: at the bottom, Watergate's spying attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I've had the opportunity to write that technology now advances in crabs, i.e. backstages.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized the communications, the Internet restored a telegraph on wire (telephone).
The videocassettes (analogues) had allowed cinema researchers to explore a step-by-step film, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (numerics) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while on the plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not extraordinary, therefore, that communication policies and techniques return to the horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was in the secret of the embassies.
The embassies are now asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France bids its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review compliance with the fast-deployed funding promises (such as fast-start or early funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French bidouillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU played a major role in convincing its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large-scale event, brochure distribution...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated for its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with a level of precision.
The EU announces that in 2010 EUR 2.2 billion has been released, which puts it on the right track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen "new and additional" agreement, in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of the Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France had blocked the procedure.
Today, each one chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has considered as a reference in 2009: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or at the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total support for developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justified: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation based on more efficient technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro given to it... Moreover, it should not be counted as the cost of lending to the lender country (i.e. an interest rate equivalent).
But France has only made such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-pass tour!
In summary, in its fast start funding, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action in time and on the other on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she is able to claim that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that Bercy has achieved arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend ?) and in the negotiations as developing countries are not entirely due to...
The chapter on early funding is only a relatively short-term issue, compared with the overall climate discussion.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): there will be no escape from the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of such a nature to increase the level of international confidence needed to advance in the discussions.
